Web Application Security Testing Lab
Skills: OWASP Top 10, SQL injection, XSS, authentication flaws
Tools: Burp Suite, OWASP Juice Shop, DVWA
Outcome: Pen test report with screenshots

A web application security assessment was conducted against two intentionally vulnerable applications: DVWA (Damn Vulnerable Web Application) and OWASP Juice Shop. The purpose of this assessment was to identify common web vulnerabilities aligned with the OWASP Top 10 using manual testing techniques and Burp Suite.
The assessment identified multiple high-risk vulnerabilities, including SQL Injection, Cross-Site Scripting (XSS), and authentication and access control weaknesses. These issues demonstrate improper input handling, insufficient output encoding, and weak session management.
Overall, the applications exhibit vulnerabilities that could allow attackers to access sensitive data, execute client-side attacks, and bypass security controls.

Applications Tested:
•	DVWA (hosted locally) 
•	OWASP Juice Shop (hosted locally via Docker) 
Tools Used:
•	Burp Suite Community Edition 
•	Firefox (proxy configured) 
•	Docker 
Testing Methodology:
•	Manual testing 
•	Request interception and modification 
•	Repeater-based testing 
•	OWASP Top 10 alignment

Methodology
Testing was conducted by intercepting HTTP and HTTPS traffic using Burp Suite. Requests were analyzed and modified using the Repeater tool to evaluate how user-controlled input was processed by the server.

The following methodology was used:
•	Identify input fields and API endpoints 
•	Capture requests via proxy 
•	Modify parameters (GET, POST, JSON) 
•	Analyze server responses 
•	Confirm vulnerability behavior 
•	Document findings with evidence 

Findings

Finding 1: SQL Injection
Application: DVWA
Severity: High
OWASP Category: Injection
Endpoint:
/vulnerabilities/sqli/
Description:
The application fails to properly validate user input in the id parameter. Manipulating this parameter alters the backend database query, allowing the retrieval of unintended data, like the name and surname of user, as seen in the screenshot below.
Evidence:
A modified request resulted in multiple user records being returned instead of a single result.
Impact:
•	Unauthorized access to database contents 
•	Potential data leakage 
•	Possible authentication bypass 
Solution:
•	Use parameterized queries (prepared statements) 
•	Validate and sanitize input 
•	Avoid dynamic SQL queries 
